  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and legal evidence across borders\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Common standards for:\n- Customer due diligence\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Compliance mechanisms\n\n4. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International organizations can impose sanctions\n- Coordinated efforts to track and freeze illicit financial assets\n- Pressure on non-compliant jurisdictions\n\n5. Information Sharing\n- Global financial intelligence networks\n- Cross-border reporting mechanisms\n- Collaborative databases tracking suspicious transactions\n\n6. Compliance Obligations\n- Financial institutions required to follow international and national regulations\n- Risk-based approaches to preventing money laundering\n- Consistent reporting standards\n\nThese intersections create a complex but integrated global approach to combating financial crimes.",
